{"key":"processedPost-9501784","value":{"id":9501784,"first":9496362,"last":9501784,"when":1230402890,"utime":"12/27/08 08:34 PM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br />I have no idea how it's able to measure this, as the moisture content is the same the whole time - but it definitely is the case. <img style=\"max-width:192px;height:auto;\" src=\"https://files.shroomery.org/smileys/shrug.gif\" alt=\":shrug:\" title=\":shrug:\"/></blockquote><br />As air heats, the molecules expand, thus it can hold more moisture.&nbsp; A hygrometer does not measure <i>total</i> moisture in the air, it measures RELATIVE humidity, which is a measure of the <i>capacity</i> of the air to hold water.&nbsp; A 20F rise in temperature allows the air to hold roughly twice as much moisture.&nbsp; Therefore, if your air is at 50% humidity and 70F, a drop to 50F, would lower the temperature to the dewpoint and you'd have 100% humidity.<br />RR","title":"Re: humidistat"}}